These steps outline the general steps to get a initrd image that talks to trustee to fetch a key
and decrypt a root image.

1. Compile trustee-attester
git clone https://github.com/confidential-containers/guest-components.git
cd attestation-agent
cargo build -p kbs_protocol --bin trustee-attester --no-default-features --features "background_check,passport,openssl,bin,snp-attester"

If all succeeds, the binary will be target/debug/trustee-attester

2. Copy the binary to /usr/bin/trustee-attester and do a trial run, make sure you are able to fetch secrets from your trustee setup:
trustee-attester --url http://kbs-service.trustee-operator-system:8080 get-resource --path default/keyvaluepairs/key1

3. Files overview:
dracut/dracut.conf -> This makes sure that the sev_guest module is part of the initrd image we will build
Copy this to /etc/dracut.conf

dracut/65aaclient/ -> This folder has a script called module-setup.sh that includes all custom required binaries
in our initrd image. Take a look at the script and make sure all required binaries/config files are included.
Copy the entire directory to /usr/lib/dracut/modules.d/

scripts/aa-client-service.sh -> This is where the primary logic is for our trustee demo. Copy this over to
/usr/bin/aa-client-service.sh

systemd/aa-client.service -> The systemd file, copy this over to  /usr/lib/systemd/system/

4. Guest setup:
For best results, *install* a guest VM from scratch. Manually partition the disk and make sure to enable LUKS for the
root. For simplicity, choose standard partition although LVM should work.

5. Once all files are in place, make a backup of your initrd image so that you can select it from grub if things
go wrong.
Finally, regenerate the initrd image: dracut -f

6. Use lsinitrd to make sure the newly generated initrd image has everything we need.
For example, to check if the trustee-attester binary is included:
lsinitrd /boot/initramfs-5.14.0-553.el9.x86_64.img | grep trustee-attester
-rwxr-xr-x   1 root     root     21374320 Nov 28 11:55 usr/bin/trustee-attester

To check, if the sev-guest kernel module is present:
[root@sev-vm2 ~]# lsinitrd /boot/initramfs-5.14.0-553.el9.x86_64.img | grep sev
drwxr-xr-x   2 root     root            0 Nov 28 11:55 usr/lib/modules/5.14.0-553.el9.x86_64/kernel/drivers/virt/coco/sev-guest
-rw-r--r--   1 root     root        13424 Nov 28 11:55 usr/lib/modules/5.14.0-553.el9.x86_64/kernel/drivers/virt/coco/sev-guest/sev-guest.ko.xz

7. Reboot to the newly generated initrd image.

8. Debugging:
aa-client-service.sh has "info" to pretty-print messages during boot. Replace them with "echo" and run
journalctl -b > boot.log to retrace steps in the script if something goes wrong.





